idCitation.resTitle: India 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex: Second-Order Administrative Divisions, 2000-2020

dataIdInfo.idPurp: The U.S. Census Bureau is providing annual subnational five-year age group population estimates by sex for 2000 to 2020 in a geographic information system (GIS) for users of the Spatial Data Repository, funded by the U.S. President’s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).
dataIdInfo.idAbs: Annual five-year age group population estimates by sex for 2000 to 2020 for the second-order administrative divisions of India were prepared by the U.S. Census Bureau for joining (linking) to this boundary shapefile as attribute data. The estimates are consistent with the midyear national projections from the U.S. Census Bureau International Data Base (IDB).

Consts.useLimit:
• U.S. Census Bureau population estimates: None. The population estimates were provided by the U.S. Census Bureau. Acknowledgment of the Census Bureau would be appreciated in products derived from these data.

  • Shapefile: The GADM shapefile input has the following limitation: "This dataset is freely available for academic use and other non-commercial use. Redistribution, or commercial use is not allowed without prior permission."

  • Census data: Data can be downloaded from the India 2011 census websites cited in the "Credits" section without prior permission from the Regsitrar General of India. However, usage beyond downloading might require permission.

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
SUBNATIONAL DIVISIONS
India’s first-order administrative divisions: 29 states and 7 union territories; India’s second-order administrative divisions: 674 districts as of 2014.
SHAPEFILE
The GADM shapefile, from 2014, contained polygons for 2,340 third-order administrative divisions. The U.S. Census Bureau did the following, beginning with this shapefile, to obtain a final shapefile: • It dissolved the GADM shapefile into a shapefile that contained 666 polygons representing India’s second-order administrative divisions, its districts. • It added polygons for the 9 districts of Delhi, replacing the single polygon for the National Capital Territory from the GADM shapefile. • It aligned the boundaries in the new shapefile to the “Large Scale International Boundary Line” polygon file (2012) from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues to create the final shapefile. The Census Bureau cannot guarantee the precision of the boundary placements.
The polygon for the district Koch Bihar, in the state of West Bengal, includes the enclaves in Bangladesh. The enclaves (along with the Bangladesh-controlled enclaves in India) are being dissolved as of 2015-2016. However, the Census Bureau has not altered the shapefile to reflect these changes as the enclaves existed when enumeration for the 2011 census took place.
CENSUS DATA
The CENSUS OF INDIA 2011 Table C-14 contains 5-year age groups, the open-ended age groups of 80-and-over, and unstated age groups, all by sex, for the first-order divisions (states and union territories) and the second-order administrative divisions (districts). The Census Bureau made an updated version of Table C-14 so that it included the following: • The state of Telangana, formed in 2014, containing 10 districts that were split from Andhra Pradesh, making the total of states 29. • The districts in the 2014 GADM shapefile that were not listed in the original table from the 2011 census, bringing the total number of districts from 640 as of the census to 674 as of 2014. (Any districts formed subsequent to the 2014 GADM shapefile are not included in the updated table.)
The 10 districts that form Telangana were determined from the boundary-change information from Statoids and from maps in the MapsofIndia.com website. Populations for the age groups by sex for Telangana are the aggregates of the 2011 census populations for those groups for the 10 districts.
2011 populations for the districts that were formed between the 2011 census and 2014, based on the GADM shapefile, were determined as follows: • First, by consulting maps of the new districts from the MapsofIndia.com website that showed their third-order administrative divisions (sub-districts and tehsils); • Second, by aggregating the total populations for both sexes, males, and females for those sub-districts and tehsils from the Primary Census Abstract, citied in the credits, to the districts. Populations from the 2011 census by age groups were not available for the districts formed after 2011. The age group distributions by percent for the males and females from the original districts from which they were split were adopted.
The unstated populations were distributed proportionally to the 5-year and open-ended age group populations by sex.
Total populations from the 2001 census for the states and union territories were obtained from Table C-14: “Population in five year age-group by residence and sex." The table also contained total populations for the 593 districts in place as of that census. The 2001 census population for Telangana is the aggregate of the populations of its 10 districts, whose boundaries were unchanged between the 2001 and 2011 censuses.
Based on the reported 2001 and 2011 census numbers, the population between the censuses declined only for the northeastern state of Nāgāland. The populations for the other states and union territories grew.
2000-2020 ESTIMATES
The estimates for the 5-year age groups between ages 0 to 79 and for ages 80-and-over by sex for 2000 to 2020 were calculated for the 674 districts in place as of 2014 and then aggregated for the 29 states and 7 union territories. Basing the calculations on the 2001-2011 intercensal trends at the district level was not feasible, given that the number of districts grew from 593 as of the 2001 census to 674 as of 2014 based on the GADM shapefile. The calculations therefore are based on the intercensal trends of the state and union territory populations. The calculations were done in two steps:
(1) Total population controls for the 29 states and 7 union territories for 2000 to 2020 were calculated using the Logistic Growth Rate method, and those controls are consistent with the 2000-2020 estimates and projections for India from the INTERNATIONAL DATA BASE. Total population controls for the 674 districts for 2000 to 2020 were calculated by prorating their 2011 census populations to their state or union territory total population controls for those years.
(2) The 5-year age group estimates for the districts were calculated using the Iterative Proportional Fitting method, based on the age group populations from the 2011 census (and aggregated for the states and union territories). The estimates are consistent with both the controls from step 1 and the 5-year age group estimates and projections by sex for India from the INTERNATIONAL DATA BASE.
The Logistic Growth Rate and Iterative Proportional Fitting methods are described in the document “Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas,” and web addresses for accessing it are given at the end of this section.
FEATURE AND ATTRIBUTE DETAILS
The 2000-2020 population estimates for the 29 states and 7 union territories (and for the second-order administrations, 674 districts) are provided in the following 2 tables: • The Unicode tab-delimited text file (table) "India_5yr_age_sex_2000-2020_uscb_aug2016.txt,” which can be joined to the shapefile via the common field “GEO_MATCH." • The Excel table “India_5yr_age_sex_2000-2020_508_uscb_aug16.xlsx,” formatted for accessibility in compliance with Section 508 of the U.S. Government’s Federal Rehabilitation Act.
For the subnational areas the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN) “approved” names from the NGA GEOnet Names Server (cited in “Credits”) were used. For any area that a BGN name was not available, the name from the national census was used. Official codes for the subnational areas from the country’s national statistical office, when available, are entered in the “NSO_CODE” field in both the text and Excel tables. Information on any alternate area names or recent name or boundary changes is entered in the “COMMENT” field.
A partial listing of the fields in the tables in both the Excel and Unicode text files, including those containing the age group populations for both sexes, males, and females for the year 2000 (whose field headings are denoted “B,” “M,” and “F” respectively), follows:
AREA_NAME GEO_MATCH (identical to the shapefile GEO_MATCH field for the join) GEO_LABEL COUNTRY ADM1_NAME ADM2_NAME ADM3_NAME ADM_LEVEL COMMENT GENC FIPS NSO_CODE BTOTL_2000 B0004_2000 B0509_2000 B1014_2000 B1519_2000 B2024_2000 B2529_2000 B3034_2000 B3539_2000 B4044_2000 B4549_2000 B5054_2000 B5559_2000 B6064_2000 B6569_2000 B7074_2000 B7579_2000 B80PL_2000 MTOTL_2000 M0004_2000 M0509_2000 M1014_2000 M1519_2000 M2024_2000 M2529_2000 M3034_2000 M3539_2000 M4044_2000 M4549_2000 M5054_2000 M5559_2000 M6064_2000 M6569_2000 M7074_2000 M7579_2000 M80PL_2000 FTOTL_2000 F0004_2000 F0509_2000 F1014_2000 F1519_2000 F2024_2000 F2529_2000 F3034_2000 F3539_2000 F4044_2000 F4549_2000 F5054_2000 F5559_2000 F6064_2000 F6569_2000 F7074_2000 F7579_2000 F80PL_2000… The age and sex group sequence repeats for the years 2001 to 2020.
Descriptions of the fields can be found in the “Data_Dictionary” tab in the Excel table.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION
More detail on the U.S. Census Bureau subnational age and sex group estimates and maps for PEPFAR can be found in the document “Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository,” and it includes a data dictionary identical to that in the Excel table. Web addresses to access the document are given below.
ACCESS
The U.S. Census Bureau’s products for PEPFAR can be accessed from the following websites in the SPATIAL DATA REPOSITORY:
Zipped file containing geographic boundary data, tables with subnational population estimates, and instructions for linking (joining) the text file to the geographic boundary data: http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/home/. This web address also provides access to data and maps from the DHS (Demographic and Health Surveys) Program.
Instructions for linking the text file to the geographic boundary data can also be found at http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/references/ReadMe_PopLinkageToShapefile_Instructions.pdf.
Methods documents:
“Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository”: http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/references/geo_metadata_pgs_uscb_v4_sep16.pdf.
“Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas”: http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/references/subntl_pop_est_methods_pgs_uscb_sep16.pdf.
All of the above documents, tables, and geographic boundary data (zipped) can also be accessed through the U.S. CENSUS BUREAU, INTERNATIONAL PROGRAMS, SUBNATIONAL MAPPING FOR ADMINISTRATIVE AREAS: U.S. PRESIDENT’S EMERGENCY PLAN FOR AIDS RELIEF, available at http://www.census.gov/population/international/data/mapping/spatialdata.html.

CENSUS DATA
(1) Registrar General and Census Commissioner, India (2011). CENSUS OF INDIA 2011. Table C-14: “Population in five year age-group by residence and sex" (by country, states, and union territories). Accessed from http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/C-series/C-14.html in September 2015. The table contained data for the following two administrative levels: 28 states and 7 union territories, 640 districts. (2) Registrar General and Census Commissioner, India (2011). CENSUS OF INDIA 2011. "Primary Census Abstract Data Tables,” available at http://censusindia.gov.in/pca/pcadata/pca.html, accessed in December 2015. The table contained data for the following four administrative levels: 28 states and 7 union territories, 640 districts, 5,988 sub-districts (tehsils), and 8,067 urban towns and numerous rural villages. (3) Registrar General and Census Commissioner, India. CENSUS OF INDIA 2001. Table C-14: “Population in five year age-group by residence and sex" (by country, states, and union territories). Accessed through Census Digital Library, http://www.censusindia.gov.in/DigitalLibrary/Tables.aspx, in June 2016. The table contained total populations for the first- and second-order administrative divisions from the 2001 census.
SHAPEFILES
(1) Hijmans, Robert et al. (2014). "India." Global Administrative Boundaries (GADM) Project. Accessed from http://www.gadm.org/download in February 2016. (2) “Large Scale International Boundary Line” polygon file (2012), U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues, available at https://hiu.state.gov/data/data.aspx, accessed in 2016.
NATIONAL ESTIMATES AND PROJECTIONS
U.S. Census Bureau, Population Division. INTERNATIONAL DATA BASE, August 2016 release, available at http://www.census.gov/population/international/data/idb/informationGateway.php, accessed in August 2016.
NATIONAL AND SUBNATIONAL AREA NAMES AND CODES
(1) U.S. National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency. NGA GEOnet Names Server (GNS), available at http://geonames.nga.mil/gns/html/, accessed in July 2016. For geographic area names from the U.S. Board on Geographic Names and the U.S. Government Federal Information Processing System (FIPS) codes. (2) U.S. Government Geopolitical Entities, Names, and Codes (GENC) Standard. NGS Standards Registry, available at https://nsgreg.nga.mil/genc/discovery, accessed in July 2016.

Listed the districts that were split from Andhra Pradesh to form the state of Telangana (3) Law, Gwillim (2016). "India Districts."
